    <item>
      <title>Re: Design-a-Weapon catagory 1H Shieldmate</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&amp;message.id=15905#M15905</link>
      <description>When it comes to tanking very hard hitting mobs, the thing that kills tanks is damage spikes.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I define a dangerous damage spike as one high enough and prolonged enough that healers cannot adapt and heal fast enough prior to the tank dieing, or simply cannot keep up with the total dps of a mob.&amp;nbsp; 2000 mean dps is more like 1000-1500 dps most of the time, with nasty spikes to 3000+.&amp;nbsp; The 1500 or 2000 dps isn't what kills the tank.&amp;nbsp; It's that spike to 3-4k that erodes your hitpoints before healing can adapt.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;You can reduce the probability of a lethal damage spike in two ways- increase hitpoints, or increase mitigation.&amp;nbsp; Both have a profound effect on reducing the probability of a lethal spike.&amp;nbsp; The difference is.... the AC will reduce the effects of the spike (smaller damage spike, or no damage spike), the hitpoints will give you a larger cushion to stay alive until heals catch up (the spike still happens, you just have a little extra time to live before the healing catches up).&amp;nbsp; Higher mitigation will also reduce the average damage/sec taken, reducing total healing requirements while tanking.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Defensive reduces the value of mitigation, by halving the DI value of a mob (that's a key reason knights are sometimes rabidly focused on AC).&amp;nbsp; However, even for a warrior... when do you need the extra tanking help from AC the most?&amp;nbsp; While under defensive, or after it's gone?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The thing is about raid mobs, they generally have high atk.&amp;nbsp; This *increases* the value and importance of AC.&amp;nbsp; On an exp mob, if you have pretty good AC you'll often start to get into the upper portion of the mitigation curve where mitigation starts to approach its limit and the slope decreases.&amp;nbsp; On a raid boss, you're not likely to reach that point until you're WELL past it in progression.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;It may well be that a balanced approach to AC vs HP is the best way.... it's very difficult to prove the relative value of HP and AC, and then it only applies to a given mob under a given set of parameters (ie, it changes.... a lot).&amp;nbsp; I am, however, totally mystified by tanks of all types (including warriors) who ignore AC augs and focus fully on hitpoints.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Anyways, the fact many of the top AC people on EQRankings are knights does not indicate a class balance problem, as some would like you to believe.&amp;nbsp; It reflects personal choices, based on easily obtainable items that are available to all classes.&amp;nbsp; If a warrior has focused so much on hp that knights far below them in progression out-mitigate them- well, that's their own problem created by poor decisions on their part.&amp;nbsp; That top end knight that focused heavily on AC has dramatically less hitpoints than many other knights and warriors- they made a sacrifice for it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
